ğŸ“Œ Overview

Today I learned about Docker Network Management, which is essential for controlling communication between containers and maintaining an organized Docker environment. I explored commands used to list, inspect, remove, and clean unused Docker networks.

ğŸ§  Technologies Learned

Docker Networking

Network Management Commands

ğŸ” Listing Docker Networks

To view all available Docker networks:

docker network ls

âœ… Purpose

Displays all networks along with:

Network ID

Network Name

Driver

Scope

ğŸ§± Default Docker Networks

Docker automatically creates three networks:

Network	Description
bridge	Default private network allowing container-to-container communication
host	Uses host machine network directly
none	Disables networking completely
ğŸ” Inspecting Docker Networks

To view detailed information about a network:

docker network inspect <network_name>

âœ… Provides Details About

Network driver

Subnet and gateway configuration

Connected containers

Container IP addresses

ğŸ’¡ Use Case

Helpful for troubleshooting and verifying container connectivity.

âŒ Removing Docker Networks

To remove a specific Docker network:

docker network rm <network_name>

âš ï¸ Important Note

Network cannot be removed if containers are connected.

Containers must be stopped or disconnected first.

ğŸ§¹ Pruning Unused Networks

To remove all unused networks:

docker network prune

âœ… Purpose

Removes networks not used by any running container

Keeps Docker environment clean and optimized

ğŸ’¡ Additional Tip
docker system prune


Also removes unused networks along with containers, images, and other unused resources.

ğŸš€ Key Learnings

Docker provides built-in default networks.

Network inspection helps understand container communication.

Removing unused networks improves system efficiency.

Proper network management is important in real-world containerized applications.

